ective indicators of quality and outcomes, and an unequal distribution of resources and outcomes across the country and among different population groups. Because of the adoption of the Affordable Care Act in 2010, and subsequent revisions to it, the U.S. is facing a period of enormous change. There is a great need to improve coverage and improve equity, better ensure quality outcomes, and find ways to better control expenditures. Health Systems in Transition: United States provides an in-depth discussion of these issues and a thorough review of the U.S. health care system.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aHealth services administrationzUnited States. 0aMedical carezUnited StatesxEvaluation. 0aMedical carezUnited StatesxFinance. 7aHEALTH & FITNESS / Health Care Issues.2bisacsh  aU.S. health system.  acomparative health systems.  ahealth care delivery.  ahealth care financing.  ahealth care organization.  ahealth care reform.  ahealth policy.  amedicare.1 aUnruh, Lynn Y., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aVaillancourt Rosenau, Pauline M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073922040uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148753932040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487539320423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487539320/original  a978-3-11-073922-0  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles